<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">08 — Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Echo Park (LA County) · Taqueria · True T-72F Walk-In Freezer</div>
        <h3>"Temp alarm went off at 6am — walk-in at 18°F when we opened"</h3>
        <p>Defrost system failure — defrost heater had burned out, and frost had been accumulating on the evaporator coils over approximately two weeks. The system had been working harder to compensate, masking the progressive performance loss until the evaporator was fully blocked and temperature began rising rapidly overnight. Classic slow-build failure that accelerated to a crisis at the end.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Manually defrosted the heavily iced evaporator (3 hours). Replaced defrost heater and defrost thermostat (replaced together — standard practice). Verified defrost timer function. Temperature recovery to 2°F within 2.5 hours of repair. Inventory assessment: frozen proteins were still crystallized at 18°F — all recovered. Enrolled in bi-annual maintenance to catch this failure pattern early — defrost heater resistance had been drifting for months before failure.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Newport Beach (Orange County) · Asian Seafood Market · Hoshizaki HWF-140 Walk-In</div>
        <h3>"Ice covering the entire floor — can barely walk inside"</h3>
        <p>Floor drain heater failure — the resistance heating element under the floor had failed, causing condensate from defrost cycles to freeze at floor level over several weeks. The ice had built up to approximately 2 inches across most of the floor surface, creating a serious slip hazard and beginning to stress the floor insulation panels at the edges. Classic freezer-specific failure with no equivalent in walk-in coolers.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Cleared floor ice with heated air blower (4 hours to fully clear). Replaced floor drain heater element with correct wattage Hoshizaki replacement. Verified drain line was clear before restoring heat. Inspected floor panel edges for moisture infiltration — found early-stage moisture at two panel joints from water pooling under the ice. Addressed joints with approved freezer sealant before damage progressed. Temperature stable at -2°F at end of call.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Thousand Oaks (Ventura County) · French Restaurant · Traulsen G20000 Walk-In</div>
        <h3>"Not holding 0°F — stays around 8–10°F regardless of thermostat setting"</h3>
        <p>Refrigerant leak on a Traulsen G20000 — slow R-404A leak at a suction line fitting had been losing charge over approximately 6 weeks. The system was cycling but unable to pull down to set temperature with reduced refrigerant charge. In Beverly Hills' warmer ambient environment compared to coastal areas, the reduced charge became critical faster than it would have elsewhere.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Located leak at suction line fitting with electronic detector and UV dye. Repaired fitting, pressure-tested system for 24 hours (virtual test — confirmed no additional loss). Recharged with correct R-404A quantity per Traulsen spec. Temperature pulled down to -2°F within 90 minutes. Installed permanent UV leak detection dye for monitoring. Advised on the fitting corrosion pattern — common on this age Traulsen in SoCal's climate (Conejo Valley marine-layer humidity contributes) — and recommended annual refrigerant checks.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Koreatown (LA County) · Seafood Market · Master-Bilt Walk-In Freezer</div>
        <h3>"Door completely frozen shut this morning — can't open it at all"</h3>
        <p>Anti-sweat heater failure — the door frame heating element had failed, allowing ice to accumulate at the gasket contact area and bond the door closed overnight. The market opens at 7am; the door had been bonded shut since approximately 3am. High-value frozen seafood inventory inside — every hour mattered given the potential for thawing if the situation had compromised the seal integrity.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Carefully freed door using controlled heat application to gasket area — no force applied to avoid door damage. Replaced anti-sweat door frame heater assembly with OEM Master-Bilt replacement. Verified door opens and closes freely through multiple cycles. Checked door gasket compression — found one section with compression fatigue; replaced to prevent recurrence. Seafood inventory completely intact at -4°F inside during the entire service call — door seal had maintained temperature despite being externally bonded.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

